InfosecPrep (Rewritten)

Target IP: 192.168.162.89
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.162.89 -p- shows there are three TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above. These ports are SSH, HTTP, and MySQL. The higher port 33060 seems to be running MySQL.

Performing an aggressive TCP port scan against the three TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.162.89 -p 22,80,33060 returns the result shown above. The web application on port 80 seems the most interesting to me, as it seems to be serving a WordPress application. The WordPress version is 5.4.2. The nmap scan also identified the disallowed entry /secret.txt inside the robots.txt. I will enumerate this application first as I do not have any logins for the SSH and MySQL.


Running Wappalyzer on the web application returns the result shown above, as it seems to be running WordPress and MySQL. Time to enumerate further.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP (WordPress 5.4.2)


The webpage shown above is displayed for this web application. I checked the source-code of this web application, but I did not find anything useful like developer comments. However, reading through the webpage of OSCP Voucher post, it mentions there is only one user called oscp on this box. Is this a valid user? Can I bruteforce the SSH application as this user? What about the MySQL application? Before attacking the other applications, I wish to enumerate this one further.


I performed a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.162.89 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html and obtained the result shown above. Nothing stands out to me, as it is the standard WordPress directory structure. I scanned the directories further using a recursive search, but I did not find anything useful. From previous search, I did find the /secret.txt entry inside the robots.txt. Time to check this.


I browsed to the http://192.168.162.89/secret.txt and obtained a base64 encoded string, as shown in the picture above in the left browser window. Using an online base64 decoder, I managed to decode the base64 string and obtained an SSH key as shown in the right browser window in the picture above. I saved this SSH key on my machine. Since I identified one user called oscp already, is this their key? Time to find out.

Exploitation

Obtaining a Foothold via SSH as oscp User


I changed the permission of the SSH key using the command chmod 400 id_rsa. Then using the command ssh oscp@192.168.162.89 -i id_rsa, I managed to login to the SSH application as the user oscp with their SSH key as shown in the picture above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as this user.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: user oscp to root by SUID Abuse Using /usr/bin/bash


Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null returns the /usr/bin/bash has SUID bit set, as shown above. Obtaining a root shell is as simple as entering /usr/bin/bash -p. Now I have a root shell, as shown in the picture above.
